  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered an illegal practice?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered an illegal practice in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to obscure the origin of the money, making it difficult for authorities to trace it back to criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other illegal enterprises.\n\nMoney laundering is typically prosecuted under both national and international laws. For example, in the United States, it is criminalized under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**, the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, and other statutes. Similarly, international organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to combat money laundering globally by setting standards and promoting effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences. It is universally recognized as a serious crime because it not only perpetuates criminal activities but also undermines the integrity of financial systems and economies.",
